 core, racialized and racist. Indeed, it was not until the early twentieth century, when racialized attitudes against fatness were already entrenched in the culture, that the medical establishment began its crusade against obesity. An important and original work, Fearing the Black Body argues convincingly that fat phobia isn’t about health at all, but rather a means of using the body to validate race, class, and gender prejudice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican American women-Social conditions. 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)-Social aspects-United States. 0aObesityxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aObesity-Social aspects-United States. 0aOverweight womenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aOverweight women-United States-Social conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican exceptionalism.  aAryan supremacy.  aBritish history.  aEnlightenment.  aJohn Harvey Kellogg.  aProtestantism.  aPuritanism.  aRenaissance art.  abeauty.  ablackness.  abody mass index.  adiets.  aembodiment.  aethnic studies.  aeugenics.  afat stigma.  afat studies.  ahealth disparities.  ahistory of medicine.  ahistory of science.  aimmigration.  aobesity.  arace.  aracism.  aslavery.  asociology of medicine.  athin ideal.  awhiteness.  awomen’s history.  awomen’s studies.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479891788.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479891788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479891788/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles